O:8:"stdClass":4:{s:3:"cid";s:17:"field:node:247063";s:7:"created";i:1515581042;s:6:"expire";i:0;s:4:"data";a:11:{s:4:"body";a:1:{s:3:"und";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:5:"value";s:4764:"<p>Technology is enabling companies to connect with employees in more ways than ever to create a more modern and customized learning experience. Recently, Oracle released a <em>Global Engagement Study</em> conducted by global market research company&nbsp;Kantar TNS, including feedback from nearly 5,000 full-time employees at organizations with 250 or more employees.</p><p>The study indicated that equipping employees with the latest technology and having accessible leaders and strong company values are important factors that can ultimately reflect an employee&rsquo;s success or failure within the company.</p><p>However, findings from the study indicate low marks when it comes to companies capitalizing on this&mdash;only 44% of respondents say that their company uses the latest technology to enable them to effectively perform in their role.</p><p>&ldquo;Employees as consumers are more plugged into technology via multiple devices (i.e. mobile, tablet, desktop) than ever before. They expect the same level of accessibility that they get in their personal lives with the technology they encounter at work,&rdquo; <a href="https://www.oracle.com/corporate/pressrelease/global-engagement-study-100416.html" target="_blank">said</a> Gretchen Alarcon, Group Vice President of HCM Product Strategy, Oracle.</p><p>&ldquo;Cloud technology enables this digital employee experience through features that can help employees learn, process and consume information in an easy way. A more modern user experience interface also reflects what they are accustomed to at home.&rdquo;</p><p><strong>Leadership</strong></p><p>The findings also express that a strong presence in leadership is the backbone for an employee feeling satisfied and engaged. The study indicates that productivity starts with onboarding: employees are unsatisfied with the process, as only 41% believe that company onboarding practices set them up for growth and success.</p><p>Not only are managers the first impressions of a company during onboarding, but they are also the first example of direction for the new worker. Only 47% of those polled viewed their leaders as visible and approachable and only 44% expressed that they have confidence in their leadership, indicating a lack of partnership between management and employees.</p><p>&ldquo;Employees ultimately decide if they would like to stay with a company within the first two weeks of employment,&rdquo; said Alarcon.</p><p>&ldquo;What this means, is that within the first 14 days, employees are already asking themselves, &lsquo;Do I think I can progress here? Do I have a manager who can be a mentor and am I getting the ability to create a network and get introduced to the right people and tools to best perform in my job?&rsquo; This is especially important when we think about development within a company&mdash;candidates want to feel the company is a good fit.&rdquo;</p><p>This&nbsp;study includes key indicators for a healthy leadership to employee relationship:</p><ul><li>Set examples of how best to communicate with those working under you</li><li>Remain extremely accessible so that people feel connected to company goals</li><li>Be actively involved in the working lives of new employees from the day they start</li><li>Use technology and digital experiences to stay in touch with team members.</li></ul><p><strong>Values, Culture and Reward</strong></p><p>What&rsquo;s more, companies are now seeing that like-minded values between the employee and the company play a huge role in employee engagement. Only an astonishing 38% say that their company is concerned about their overall well-being indicating that working towards a personally rewarding goal, while still upholding individual values can carry even more weight than monetary compensation.</p><p>Company culture mirrors these sentiments as employees are most comfortable and productive within a creative, yet flexible workplace culture. While compensation is often seen to be connected to employee satisfaction, we are now seeing that individuals are more interested in joining companies that uphold their same personal values to gauge if they are a good fit.</p><p>Whether it&rsquo;s a more flexible work schedule, more volunteer or health and wellness opportunities, companies too should now be listening and connecting with employees in more ways that correlate with their personal well-being.</p><p><em><strong><span style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400"><span style="font-weight: 400"><span style="font-weight: 400"><span style="font-weight: 400">This article first appeared on <a href="http://www.hrinasia.com/" target="_blank">HR in Asia</a>.</span></span></span></span></span></span></strong></em></p>";s:7:"summary";s:1:" ";s:6:"format";s:9:"full_html";s:10:"safe_value";s:4764:"<p>Technology is enabling companies to connect with employees in more ways than ever to create a more modern and customized learning experience. Recently, Oracle released a <em>Global Engagement Study</em> conducted by global market research company&nbsp;Kantar TNS, including feedback from nearly 5,000 full-time employees at organizations with 250 or more employees.</p><p>The study indicated that equipping employees with the latest technology and having accessible leaders and strong company values are important factors that can ultimately reflect an employee&rsquo;s success or failure within the company.</p><p>However, findings from the study indicate low marks when it comes to companies capitalizing on this&mdash;only 44% of respondents say that their company uses the latest technology to enable them to effectively perform in their role.</p><p>&ldquo;Employees as consumers are more plugged into technology via multiple devices (i.e. mobile, tablet, desktop) than ever before. They expect the same level of accessibility that they get in their personal lives with the technology they encounter at work,&rdquo; <a href="https://www.oracle.com/corporate/pressrelease/global-engagement-study-100416.html" target="_blank">said</a> Gretchen Alarcon, Group Vice President of HCM Product Strategy, Oracle.</p><p>&ldquo;Cloud technology enables this digital employee experience through features that can help employees learn, process and consume information in an easy way. A more modern user experience interface also reflects what they are accustomed to at home.&rdquo;</p><p><strong>Leadership</strong></p><p>The findings also express that a strong presence in leadership is the backbone for an employee feeling satisfied and engaged. The study indicates that productivity starts with onboarding: employees are unsatisfied with the process, as only 41% believe that company onboarding practices set them up for growth and success.</p><p>Not only are managers the first impressions of a company during onboarding, but they are also the first example of direction for the new worker. Only 47% of those polled viewed their leaders as visible and approachable and only 44% expressed that they have confidence in their leadership, indicating a lack of partnership between management and employees.</p><p>&ldquo;Employees ultimately decide if they would like to stay with a company within the first two weeks of employment,&rdquo; said Alarcon.</p><p>&ldquo;What this means, is that within the first 14 days, employees are already asking themselves, &lsquo;Do I think I can progress here? Do I have a manager who can be a mentor and am I getting the ability to create a network and get introduced to the right people and tools to best perform in my job?&rsquo; This is especially important when we think about development within a company&mdash;candidates want to feel the company is a good fit.&rdquo;</p><p>This&nbsp;study includes key indicators for a healthy leadership to employee relationship:</p><ul><li>Set examples of how best to communicate with those working under you</li><li>Remain extremely accessible so that people feel connected to company goals</li><li>Be actively involved in the working lives of new employees from the day they start</li><li>Use technology and digital experiences to stay in touch with team members.</li></ul><p><strong>Values, Culture and Reward</strong></p><p>What&rsquo;s more, companies are now seeing that like-minded values between the employee and the company play a huge role in employee engagement. Only an astonishing 38% say that their company is concerned about their overall well-being indicating that working towards a personally rewarding goal, while still upholding individual values can carry even more weight than monetary compensation.</p><p>Company culture mirrors these sentiments as employees are most comfortable and productive within a creative, yet flexible workplace culture. While compensation is often seen to be connected to employee satisfaction, we are now seeing that individuals are more interested in joining companies that uphold their same personal values to gauge if they are a good fit.</p><p>Whether it&rsquo;s a more flexible work schedule, more volunteer or health and wellness opportunities, companies too should now be listening and connecting with employees in more ways that correlate with their personal well-being.</p><p><em><strong><span style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400"><span style="font-weight: 400"><span style="font-weight: 400"><span style="font-weight: 400">This article first appeared on <a href="http://www.hrinasia.com/" target="_blank">HR in Asia</a>.</span></span></span></span></span></span></strong></em></p>";s:12:"safe_summary";s:1:" ";}}}s:10:"field_tags";a:1:{s:3:"und";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{s:3:"tid";s:3:"376";}}}s:11:"field_image";a:1:{s:3:"und";a:1:{i:0;a:18:{s:3:"fid";s:5:"57920";s:3:"uid";s:3:"306";s:8:"filename";s:47:"Are_